│ incorrect transformation.\n\nKey point: copysign on a NaN returns a NaN with  │
│ the sign of the second operand. Replacing the sign operand with a constant    │
│ alters the nan's sign even when the demanded FP-class doesn't care about sign │
│ for NaN. InstCombine must preserve exact semantics (bit pattern) for NaNs     │
│ unless we can prove NaN is impossible.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- First    │
│ transformation occurs in InstCombinerImpl::SimplifyDemandedUseFPClass at the  │
│ copysign intrinsic handling.\n- The log shows: after visiting ret, it adds a  │
│ deferred replacement: set operand 1 of copysign to -1.0 because (DemandedMask │
│ & fcPositive) == fcNone. Then it folds to fabs + fneg.\n- This modification   │
│ directly leads to different NaN sign in the target (negative) compared to     │
│ source (positive from %unknown.sign = +0.0), as shown by Alive2.\n\n3. Root   │
│ Cause Analysis:\nThe transformation assumes it's safe to force the sign of    │
│ the result when the demanded mask excludes positive classes. However,         │
│ copysign propagates the sign to NaNs as well. Changing the sign operand       │
│ changes the exact value for NaNs. Because the function's nofpclass attribute  │
│ excludes only positive finite classes (pinf, pzero, psub, pnorm) but allows   │
│ NaNs, the demanded mask does not rule out NaNs. Therefore, the replacement is │
│ not semantics-preserving when the first operand may be NaN.\n\nWe must        │
│ restrict the transform to cases where we can prove the first operand cannot   │
│ be NaN (i.e., Known info indicates NaN is impossible), otherwise we cannot    │
│ change the sign operand to a constant.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File: │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSimplifyDemanded.cpp\n- Lines:     │
│ 2014-2026\n- Change: Gate the two \"roundabout\" replacements for copysign    │
│ under a check that the first operand is known not-NaN. Compute Known for      │
│ operand 0 and only proceed if NaN is known impossible.\n\nSuggested patch     │
│ (conceptual):\n\nReplace:\n  if ((DemandedMask & fcPositive) == fcNone) {\n   │
│ // Roundabout way of replacing with fneg(fabs)\n    I->setOperand(1,          │
│ ConstantFP::get(VTy, -1.0));\n    return I;\n  }\n\n  if ((DemandedMask &     │
│ fcNegative) == fcNone) {\n    // Roundabout way of replacing with fabs\n      │
│ I->setOperand(1, ConstantFP::getZero(VTy));\n    return I;\n  }\n\nWith:\n    │
│ // Only safe to force sign when the input cannot be NaN, because changing\n   │
│ // the sign operand changes the sign bit of NaNs (affecting bit pattern).\n   │
│ KnownFPClass KnownX = computeKnownFPClass(I->getOperand(0), fcAllFlags, CxtI, │
│ Depth + 1);\n\n  if (KnownX.isKnownNever(fcNan)) {\n    if ((DemandedMask &   │
│ fcPositive) == fcNone) {\n      // Replace with fneg(fabs) by forcing sign    │
│ negative\n      I->setOperand(1, ConstantFP::get(VTy, -1.0));\n      return   │
│ I;\n    }\n    if ((DemandedMask & fcNegative) == fcNone) {\n      // Replace │
│ with fabs by forcing sign from +0.0\n      I->setOperand(1,                   │
│ ConstantFP::getZero(VTy));\n      return I;\n    }\n  }\n\nThis ensures we    │
│ only alter the sign operand when x is proven non-NaN.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe  │
│ incorrect transformation stems from forcing the sign in copysign under        │
│ demanded FP-class constraints without accounting for NaN preservation. By     │
│ guarding the replacement with a check that the first operand is known         │
│ not-NaN, we avoid changing the bit pattern of NaNs and preserve correctness.  │
│ This fix prevents the fabs/fneg rewrite when NaN is possible, eliminating the │
│ mismatch observed by Alive2 while still allowing the optimization when        │
│ safe."})                                                                      │
